<section class="ftco-section bg-light ftco-faqs">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="row">
      <div class="col-lg-7">
        <div class="heading-section mb-5 mt-5 mt-lg-0">
          <h2 class="mb-3">Animal Rescue</h2>
          <p>
            Many dogs are reported hurt, wounded, injured or subjected to
            cruelty to us. Our priority is to save the life of the dog and send
            him for medical care. Since there is a dearth of government run
            medical, boarding and lodging facilities, we are constrained to send
            them to cost effective medical boarding if the dog is not treatable
            on the spot. Once at the medical boarding, the dog is under the care
            of vet and his other requirements are taken care of.
          </p>
          <p>
            In case of a dog reported rabid, unlike popular perception, it is
            illegal to eliminate the dog. ABC Rules, Rule 10 provides that :
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="col-lg-5">
        <img width="100%" src="images/about/puppy.jpeg" alt="" />
      </div>
      <div class="col-lg-12">
        <h4>Furious or dumb rabid dogs :</h4>

        <ul>
          <li>
            On the receipt of complaints from the public to the Dog Control Cell
            of the Local Authority or on its own, the dog squad of the Local
            Authority would catch such dogs, suspected to be rabid.
          </li>
          <li>
            The caught dog would then be taken to the pound where it would be
            isolated in an isolation ward.
          </li>
          <li>
            The suspected rabid dog would then be subjected to inspection by a
            panel of two persons i.e. (i) a veterinary surgeon appointed by the
            Local Authority and (ii)a representative from an Animal Welfare
            Organisation
          </li>
          <li>
            If the dog is found to have a high probability of having rabies it
            would be isolated till it dies a natural death. Death normally
            occurs within 10 days of contracting rabies. Premature killings of
            suspected rabid dogs therefore prevents the true incidence of rabies
            from being known and appropriate action being taken
          </li>
          <li>
            ) If the dog is found not to have rabies but some other disease it
            would be handed over to the AWOs who will take the necessary action
            to cure and rehabilitate the dog
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="col-lg-12">
        <div class="heading-section mb-5 mt-5 mt-lg-0">
          <h2 class="mb-3">Sterilization</h2>
          <p>
            Sterilization and consequent neutralization of dogs is of prime
            importance for population control of dogs and easing of man animal
            and man to man conflict on streets as there is continuous struggle
            and misery for a dog on the street. They are ignored, humiliated,
            abused and starved, thrown acid, hot water due to human callousness.
            Their babies are more often packed in gunny bags and dumped in the
            garbage, poisoned or relocated and they die a painful way.
          </p>
          <p>
            Keeping this in mind, Animal Birth Control (Dogs) Rules, 2001
            envisaged that the street dogs shall be sterilized and immunized by
            participation of animal welfare organizations, private individuals
            and the local authority. Indie Dog Commune has been involved
            sterilization of dogs in coordination with authorities.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

